Still, very cool graphical interface. Sorry about the long diatribe on my quick and dirty analysis of the findings (it’s the scientist in me…)

That said, I also feel very strongly about not getting the Army corps of engineers involved in issues such as natural disaster mitigation. As a geologist by formal educational background, I’ve seen how poorly constructed natural disaster mitigation procedures have blown up in our faces (a la Katrina).

What is not really as evident in those graphics is that if the storm passed 30 miles to the SW of where it made landfall, most of Houston proper would have been on the “dirty” side of the hurricane. This would have resulted in lots more damage, not from floods, but through the increased tornado frequency. Storm surges are impactful on the refineries that dot the ship channel, but not as much of an impact on personal property (not many people prefer living by refineries, for logical reasons). However, the tornados aren’t predictable, creating major risk to personal property.

This morning I am very thankful to have a job I find meaningful.  I want to thank everyone for making it easier to get up this morning, given that I knew the place I was headed was good and right.

I think this is the main point I take away, (at least statistical, there are obviously much more important social and moral consequences to last night):

> Predictive models, generally based on historical patterns, work until they don’t.

Predictions on future elections are doomed to be based on patterns of prior elections: who is likely to vote and whom are they likely to vote for.  It’s not clear even that more data would fix this, as you would still need to learn prior behavior even at a more granular level.  Last night the patterns changed fundamentally, and what we have learned from the history of American elections was vaporized.

As I keep thinking on this I think you'd need about 30 - 50 indicators per person distilled from as many public data sets,  then the convergence of those results merged into a resultant set and scored with no respect to time. Clearly historical modeling is no longer relevant to predicting elections. It would have to be reactive enough to gauge the sentiment of a person each day and the weighting of predictors would need to slide as different things become relevant on any given day. Those would likely be driven by some kind subordinate process that would profile social traffic. In my mind I see several ds tools working in concert here, as opposed to leaning on any one or any several working in parallel but independently. Case in point: <http://www.foxnews.com/tech/2016/11/09/did-google-search-data-provide-clue-to-trumps-shock-election-victory.html>

import unicodedata

So logistic regression, by design, always recovers accurate probabilities from the training data.
That is, the *empirical* probability of the positive class in the training data is recovered.

So if the ratio of positive to negative classes in your data is 1 to 3, the predicted probabilities from your logistic regression (when applied to the training data) will always average out to a probability of 0.25.
Ther predicted probabilities from logistic regression will *allways* accurately reflect the (conditional) class balance in your training data.
There is nothing wrong with training a logistic regression on unbalanced class data.

I should say: if we have a bunch of vectors, then “If they are not normalized to be of unit length, then,  ...”

My intuition is that the dot product between 2 vectors of unit length relate to the similarity between them in terms of where they are pointing, i.e., if the angle between them is small, they are effectively pointing in the same direction (obvious in up to 3 dimensions but mathematically true in N-dimensional space).  If they are not normalized to be of unit length, then, those with the largest dot products will generally point to the same location in space while those with the smallest dot products will generally be orthogonal, however due to the interplay between the cosine of the angles and the magnitudes, it is harder to say directly which are the most similar; maybe we should then use some sort of a combination of cosine measure and distance, normalized in some way to get similarities between various vectors.
I think of the “multiply the coordinates and add” part as a computational trick, not the essence of the thing.
I should say, more precisely, “the length of the projection of X onto the unit vector"
Geometrically, I think of the dot product like this.  X (dot) (unit vector) is the projection of X onto the unit vector.
Work is not the most intuitive thing though...
So, like, if you lift an object along a path in a gravitational field, the total potential energy gained is the integral of the dot product (tangent vector to path) (dot) (gravitational field)

The point to remember is the dot product is what you get when you project one vector onto another then multiply their magnitudes, which is a very geometric interpretation. messages.text: The above code may have a typo or two, but the concept is correct. The point is to scale all of your data based on the train data. In the real world you do not want the test data to skew your scaling, and scaling it by itself would lead to overly optimistic model performance.

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y)

# Set the standard scaler object your data based on train
scaler = StandardScaler().fit(X_train)

# Scale the train data
X_train_scaled = scaler.transform(X_train)

# Scale the test data
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)
